Text: Half-a-million Ukrainians have fled to the Lviv region in western Ukraine since the Russian invasion began on Feb. 24.  In this Soviet-era apartment block, behind every window is a story.
Afghan police say explosions targeting educational centers injured at least seven children in Kabul with reports of at least three bombs detonating in a mostly Shiite neighborhood.

Russian forces have attacked along a broad front in eastern Ukraine as part of a full-scale ground offensive to take control of the country’s industrial heartland. Moscow also has continued to blockade and shell Mariupol and fire missiles at other cities.
There's stark public divide in Iran over Russia's war on Ukraine, which underscores both Tehran's tilt toward Moscow in recent years and Iran’s historic enmity with Russia. (Corrects typo.)
There's stark public divide in Iran over Russia's war on Ukraine, which underscores both Teheran's tilt toward Moscow in recent years and Iran’s historic enmity with Russia.

A decision by a federal judge in Florida to throw out a national mask mandate for public transportation across the U.S. created a confusing patchwork of rules for passengers as they navigate airports and transit systems.

Food insecurity and skyrocketing food prices will take center stage when International Monetary Fund and World Bank members meet in Washington. The loss of commodities due to Russia’s war in Ukraine is being blamed for the calamity.
A judge has ruled Amazon must reinstate a former employee who was fired in 2020 after leading a protest calling for the company to do more to protect workers against COVID-19.
California is leading a new wave of flood risk management that centers on natural engineering over structural as the nation rethinks how rivers flow amid the effects of climate change.
Voters in East Timor are choosing a president in a runoff between former independence fighters, Nobel Peace Prize laureate Jose Ramos-Horta and incumbent President Francisco “Lu Olo” Guterres.
The Transportation Security Administration says it will no longer enforce the public transportation mask mandate after a U.S. judge struck down the rule. Major airlines are making masks optional.
Amid escalating clashes, Israeli fighter jets have carried out airstrikes in the Gaza Strip, the Israeli military says. Hours earlier, Palestinian militants launched a rocket into southern Israel.

The debut of NASA’s huge moon rocket is facing more delays following a string of failed fueling tests. The next chance for a test flight will be late June or July. NASA hopes to land astronauts on the moon around 2025.

Jury selection has begun in a lawsuit brought against members of the Kardashian family by Blac Chyna. The former fiancée of Rob Kardashian says the family destroyed her TV career after the two broke up. The Kardashians have denied any wrongdoing.

The Biden administration says the U.S. is banning anti-satellite missile testing. Last year Russia launched a missile to destroy a defunct Soviet-era satellite. Both that and a test by China in 2007 resulted in widespread space debris.

Alex Jones' Infowars has filed for bankruptcy after the conspiracy theorist lost defamation lawsuits over his comments that the Sandy Hook school massacre was a hoax. Here's a look at Jones' finances and how the filing affects the court proceedings.

The Biden administration says the mask mandate covering airlines and other public transportation will not be enforced while the government decides how to respond to a judge's order striking down the rule. The CDC had recently extended the mandate to May 3.

For U.S. medical students seeking abortion training, options are under threat as states propose and enact laws to stifle education about the procedure. But some doctors-in-training who plan to perform abortions say they are undeterred.

Kimberly Guilfoyle, the fiancée of former President Trump’s eldest son, has met with the House panel investigating the Capitol riot, a person familiar with the matter says. The day of the riot, Guilfoyle spoke at Trump's rally on the White House Ellipse.

"Black-ish" was a network TV rarity: A depiction of a prosperous, tight-knit family of color with Black people shaping their stories.

With the final episode set to air Tuesday, its creator and fans reflect on the sitcom's cultural impact.

The Ukrainian military says street battles have begun in the town of Kreminna and no one can evacuate. It's one of two spots where Ukraine says the Russians have managed to break through along a front in the east stretching hundreds of miles.
Twitter has put a major roadblock in front of Elon Musk’s effort to take over the company, leaving investors to wonder about the mercurial Tesla CEO’s next move. Musk has a number of options.

Some doctors say it’s time to rename low-grade prostate cancer.

Most prostate cancers are harmless, but doctors say fear of the name can cause some patients to overreact and opt for unneeded surgery or radiation.

Sherri Papini has pleaded guilty Monday to faking her own kidnapping and lying to the FBI about it, leaving her motive unanswered in the carefully planned hoax that set off a massive three-week search before she resurfaced on Thanksgiving Day in 2016.

Migrants attempted to cross the U.S.-Mexico border at the highest level in two decades last month.

The U.S. is preparing for even larger numbers with the expected lifting of a pandemic-era order that turned away asylum seekers.

Police in South Carolina have announced the arrest of a second person connected to a shootout inside a busy shopping mall in the state's capital, one of two mass shootings in the state over the Easter holiday weekend.

Federal authorities say they will not criminally charge the former Chicago police officer convicted of murder in the 2014 shooting of Black teenager Laquan McDonald.

Officials said the decision was made after consulting with the McDonald family.

Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy says Russia's offensive to take control of eastern Ukraine is in full swing.

The move was anticipated after Russia announced last month that it would concentrate on the Donbas.

Yemen's Houthi rebels have agreed to rid their ranks of child soldiers, who have fought by the thousands during the country's seven years of civil war.

More than 10,200 children have been killed or maimed in the conflict, the U.N. says.
Cosmonauts Oleg Artemyev and Denis Matveev conducted a spacewalk aboard the International Space Station to install and connect a control panel for a robotic arm.

Several college students left Ukraine in the middle of the war with Russia to attend a conference on diplomacy in New York City.

Now, they have to make a choice: Go back to Ukraine, or return home after the war has ended.
Cristiano Ronaldo says one of his newborn twins has died. The Manchester United striker and his partner, Georgina Rodriguez, announced last year that they were expecting twins.

A federal judge in Florida has voided the national mask mandate covering airplanes and other public transportation as exceeding the authority of U.S. health officials.

The mask mandate was recently extended by the Biden administration until May 3.
Three mass shootings in the U.S. over the Easter holiday weekend capped a monthlong spate of gun violence that has touched both big cities and rural communities across the nation.

Pakistan court sentenced six people to death and nine others to life in prison after convicting them for their roles in last year’s vigilante killing of a Sri Lankan factory manager accused by workers of committing blasphemy, a defense lawyer said.
Sheriff's deputies captured video of a large alligator crawling through a front yard in Florida before making its way into a community lake.

Monday is Tax Day, the federal deadline for individual tax filing and payments.

Nina Tross, executive director of the National Society of Tax Professionals, said that if people haven’t filed their taxes by now, “they’re better off filing an extension.”

Undaunted by soggy skies, President Joe Biden and first lady Jill Biden kicked off the first White House Easter Egg Roll since before the coronavirus pandemic, welcoming some 30,000 kids and adults for the all-day event.

Peres Jepchirchir of Kenya wins women’s division of the Boston Marathon, pulling ahead of Ethiopia’s Ababel Yeshaneh in the final 385 yards.

Jepchirchir finished in 2 hours, 21 minutes, 1 second — four seconds ahead.
Pioneering hip hop artist Keith Grayson, who performed as DJ Kay Slay and worked with top stars, has died of complications from COVID-19. He was 55.

Evans Chebet of Kenya wins the Boston Marathon with an unofficial time of 2 hours, 6 minutes, 50 seconds.

The men's lead pack winnowed to two as it came out of Heartbreak Hill, then Chebet pulled away from Gabriel Geay of Tanzania with four miles to go.

Twitter is trying to thwart billionaire Elon Musk's takeover attempt using a financial device that companies have wielded against unwelcome suiters for decades, the “poison pill.” Here's how that works.

As climate change intensifies hurricanes, cities along the Louisiana coast and Mississippi River are hoping President Joe Biden’s $1.2 trillion infrastructure package will bring badly needed funding to fortify flood protections.

Thousands of people in Shanghai who test positive for COVID-19 but have few or no symptoms are being ordered into quarantine centers. The biggest is the National Exhibition and Convention Center, which has beds for 50,000 people.

For this year’s White House Easter Egg Roll, first lady Jill Biden turned the South Lawn into a school community with a variety of educational stations.

“The determined spirit of education is what we wanted to honor in this Easter Egg Roll,” Biden said.

The White House Easter Egg Roll is back for the first time since before the pandemic.

Under rainy skies, President Joe Biden and Jill Biden were hosting some 30,000 kids and adults for an event the first lady dubbed the “egg-ucation roll.”

Four orphaned bear cubs have been released back into the wild in California after six months in captivity. 

Three of the bears were released in Central California's Mariposa County near where they were found.

For U.S. medical students seeking abortion training, options are under threat as states propose and enact laws to stifle education about the procedure. But some doctors-in-training who plan to perform abortions say they are undeterred.

The Boston Marathon is underway. It’s the first time the prestigious race has been run on Patriots' Day, its traditional springtime slot, since the pandemic began.

More than 28,000 people were signed up to race.

Bornean orangutan Kitra had her first baby on April 13.

The pair are doing well and bonding in the zoo's special maternity den. It will be several weeks before the unnamed baby's gender is known.

A container ship the size of three football fields was dislodged from the Chesapeake Bay on Sunday more than a month after it ran aground. The Ever Forward was refloated with the help of a high spring tide by two barges and five tugboats.

The outskirts of the northern Ukrainian city of Chernihiv lay in ruins with the landscape dotted with destroyed Russian military equipment — evidence of a chaotic retreat. 

Some 70 miles northeast of Kyiv, Chernihiv bore the brunt of the early stages of the invasion.

Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy presented military personnel with awards, thanking the officers for their service, wishing them good health, and noting that their families could be proud of their work.

Infowars has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection as the website’s founder and conspiracy theorist Alex Jones faces defamation lawsuits over his comments that the Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting was a hoax.

Russian missiles killed at least seven people in the western Ukrainian city of Lviv, Ukrainian officials said. Moscow’s troops have stepped up strikes on key infrastructure to wear down the country’s ability to resist a major ground offensive in the east.

A global computer chip shortage has made it harder for consumers to get their hands on cars, computers and other modern-day necessities. Congress is looking to boost chip manufacturing and research in the United States with billions of federal dollars.

Turkey has launched a new ground and air cross-border offensive against Kurdish militants in northern Iraq. Turkey's defense minister says Turkish jets and artillery struck targets belonging to the Kurdistan Workers’ Party.

Survivors of war crimes committed during Bosnia’s 1992-95 war say the victims of ongoing human rights abuses in Ukraine should learn from their experience of fighting for justice - reaching it will inevitably be a lengthy and painful process.
Russian missile strikes on the western Ukrainian city of Lviv caused fatalities, local officials say. Plumes of thick, black smoke were rising over Lviv after the explosions.
Ukraine vows to "fight absolutely to the end” in Mariupol, where the ruined port city's last known pocket of resistance is holed up in a sprawling steel plant laced with tunnels.

"Deliberate terror." Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said Russian troops in southern Ukraine have been carrying out torture and kidnappings. In the north, he said, indiscriminate shelling in Kharkiv has killed and wounded scores of civilians.

China’s economic growth edged up to a still-weak 4.8% over a year earlier in the first three months of 2022, as spreading coronavirus outbreaks prompted shutdowns of major industrial cities, including Shanghai.
@AP At one 50,000-bed quarantine center, a woman named Beibei, who was ordered there after a positive test, spoke of overcrowding, poorly maintained bathrooms, lack of hot showers and other issues.

@AP It's part of official efforts to contain China’s biggest coronavirus outbreak since the 2-year-old pandemic began. But it's also testing patience of people increasingly fed up with China's harsh “zero-COVID” policy that aims to isolate every case.

With the city of 25 million in lockdown, thousands of people in Shanghai who test positive for COVID-19 but have few or no symptoms are being ordered into quarantine centers in immense exhibition halls and other buildings.

@AP Musk, in an interview at the TED 2022 conference, said he had funding to take Tesla private in 2018. He called the Securities and Exchange Commission a profane name and said he only settled because bankers told him they would stop providing capital.
A group of Tesla shareholders suing CEO Elon Musk over some 2018 tweets about taking the company private is asking a federal judge to order Musk to stop commenting on the case.

Oded Goldreich was awarded the Israel Prize, the country's highest honor, last year. But the computer science professor only collected the prize this past week following criticism by Israeli nationalists to his opposition to Israel's West Bank occupation.

"We will fight absolutely to the end, to the win, in this war." Ukrainian fighters holed up in a steel plant in the last known pocket of resistance inside the shattered port city of Mariupol ignored a surrender-or-die ultimatum from the Russians.
@AP Two minors are dead and at least 31 people are injured in three mass shootings in the U.S. over the Easter holiday weekend. A suspect has been arrested in just one of the shootings.

Ukrainian volunteers in a village near Kyiv are retrieving bodies buried in mass graves amid the Russian occupation as part of an effort to investigate possible war crimes. On a street lined with walnut trees, four caskets were exhumed on Sunday.

Pittsburgh Police Chief Scott Schubert said two people died in the shooting and eight more were being treated for gunshot wounds — revising earlier numbers that said nine were injured. Authorities didn't immediately release information about any suspects.
BREAKING: South Carolina authorities say at least nine people were injured in a shooting at a club in Hampton County early Sunday. It's the second mass shooting in the state in two days.

A crowded field of Democrats is trying to figure out a winning strategy to unseat Republican Sen. Ron Johnson in Wisconsin in November. It's one of a handful of competitive Senate races this election year that could help decide Senate control.

“All this land is in blood, and it will take years to recover.”

In towns around Kyiv, bodies buried amid the Russian occupation are being retrieved for investigations into possible war crimes. More than 900 civilian victims have been found so far.

Two minors were killed and at least nine more people wounded in a shooting at a house party in Pittsburgh early Sunday, police said. The shooting happened around 12:30 a.m. at a short-term rental property where there were more than 200 people inside.

Judaism’s Passover, Christianity’s Easter and Islam’s holy month of Ramadan are coinciding this month with holy days for Buddhists, Baha’is, Sikhs, Jains and Hindus.

That convergence is inspiring a range of interfaith events.

Monday is Tax Day — the federal deadline in the U.S. for individual tax filing and payments, when the IRS will receive tens of millions of last-minute filings electronically and through paper forms.

Here’s what to know if you still have to file.

A Ukrainian health official says that at least five people have been killed by Russian shelling in Kharkiv, Ukraine’s second-largest city. Another 13 residents were wounded by Sunday’s shelling, the official said.

Palestinian medical officials say 17 people were wounded in clashes with Israeli police in Jerusalem. The unrest broke out Sunday after Israeli police entered the Al-Asqa Mosque compound to secure the spot for Jewish visitors, the officials said.

For many Christians, this weekend marks the first time in three years they will gather in person to celebrate Easter Sunday.

“The gift of being in the same physical space for the first time in three years is so grounding and beautiful,” said one pastor.

China says it will launch three more astronauts to its newest space station in June. The crew will spend six months on the Tiangong to add two modules to the space station.

The previous crew returned this weekend following a six-month stay in orbit.
Russian forces appear to be on the brink of capturing Mariupol. They have given Ukrainian fighters in the port city a deadline to surrender or be killed.
Pope Francis celebrates Easter Sunday Mass in front of tens of thousands in St. Peter's Square for the first time since the start of the pandemic. By @fdemilio

In his nightly address, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said his military needs more support from the West to have a chance at saving the coastal city of Mariupol, besieged by Russian forces. Zelenskyy called the situation in Mariupol “inhuman.”
North Korea said it has successfully test-fired a newly developed tactical guided weapon, the latest in a spate of launches that come amid stalled nuclear talks with the U.S.

@AP Specialty Records "paralleled, and perhaps defined, the evolution of Black popular music, from the 'race' music of the 1940s to the rock 'n roll of the 1950s," music historian Billy Vera wrote in the liner notes to "The Specialty Story," a five-CD set.

Music executive Art Rupe, whose Specialty Records was a premier label during the formative years of rock ‘n roll and helped launch the careers of Little Richard, Sam Cooke and many others, has died at 104.

For WNBA star Brittney Griner, playing in Russia during the offseason has turned into a nightmare, after she was detained a week before Russia invaded Ukraine. Here's what other WNBA players told @DougFeinberg about their own Russia experiences.

The U.S. Food and Drug Administration is investigating Lucky Charms cereal after dozens of customers complained of falling ill after eating it. Cereal maker General Mills said it is aware of those reports but has not found evidence of such illness.

@AP “Everybody was trying to get outside,” said Daniel Johnson, who was with his family at the mall's food court when the shooting started. “When I was coming out, you could see baby strollers turned over, people’s phones and left keys.”

@AP While no fatalities have been reported, authorities said eight of the victims were taken to the hospital. Of those eight, two were in critical condition and six were stable. The victims ranged in age from 15 to 73.
BREAKING: Ten people have been shot at a mall in South Carolina, and two others were injured in the aftermath. Authorities say three possible suspects have been detained.

A “pioneer in the defense of human rights, peace and democracy in Mexico.” Rosario Ibarra, whose long struggle to learn the fate of her disappeared son helped develop Mexico's human rights movement, has died at 95.
The Invictus Games for injured and ill service personnel and veterans have opened with a standing ovation for Ukrainian team members who left their war-torn nation to compete.

BREAKING: Multiple people have been injured in a shooting at a shopping mall in Columbia, South Carolina’s capital, police said. Police said they are evacuating Columbiana Centre and working to assess the scene.

After a two-year delay, Spanish people are returning to their traditional Easter processions, complete with bugles, drums and strange pointed headware. Some people are taking part in memory of loved ones lost to the pandemic. By @bernatarmangue

Nadiya Trubchaninova, 70, hitchhiked from her village to the shattered town of Bucha to bring her son’s body home for burial. She is one of many elderly Ukrainians who survived the first weeks of the war only to find it had taken their children.

Two pandas had an icy treat as the National Zoo celebrated 50 years of its panda exchange with China. It took Mei Xiang and her cub Xiao Qi Ji about 15 minutes to devour a “cake” made from frozen fruit juice, sweet potatoes, carrots and sugar cane.

Prince Harry and his wife Meghan got a ride on an automotive obstacle course before the opening of the Invictus Games in the Netherlands. Harry founded the games to aid the rehabilitation of injured or sick military service members and veterans.

Military veterans are helping persuade lawmakers in several conservative states to study psychedelic mushrooms for therapeutic use. 
Experts say the research is promising for treating conditions ranging from PTSD to quitting smoking.

In Alabama, emptiness claims a chair at a nurses station. It fills a teenager’s bedroom in Arizona, and floats over a wooded path in North Carolina. These are some of the spaces left behind in the U.S., where almost 1 million people have died of COVID-19.

State legislators around the country are calling it quits, in part because of the low pay. Some worry the pay discourages people of modest means from running, making legislatures less diverse racially, economically, and in terms of age and gender.

North Korean leader Kim Jong Un attended a massive civilian parade in the capital, Pyongyang, to mark the 110th anniversary of his birth of his grandfather, the country's founder.

Read more:
The death of Patrick Lyoya in Grand Rapids, Michigan, has again put the spotlight on encounters between police and Black people that begin over minor infractions but turn deadly.

At a U.S. Army training center in California's Mojave Desert, the enemy force is using social media posts to make false accusations against an American brigade. It's part of the military's effort to learn lessons from the Russian war against Ukraine.

Neil Lawyer, 84, was among the earliest to die of COVID-19 in the U.S.  

A short-term resident at a Seattle nursing home, Lawyer died within days of catching the virus. It was March 8, 2020, and the U.S. toll — now approaching 1 million — was just 30.

Clergy and lay volunteers bringing Sunday Mass to unaccompanied migrant teens in shelters in Texas say they seek to give reassurance – and find a striking witness of faith despite the youths’ loneliness and uncertain future.

The mayor of Kyiv says one person died in airstrikes as Russian forces resumed scattered attacks on the Ukrainian capital. The attacks were a reminder that the whole country remains under threat despite Russian forces' pivot to the east.

Various state lawmakers aren't seeking reelection this year, in part because of low pay. Though multiple states proposed bills to increase salaries, so far they have faltered as some legislators fear the move will rankle voters.

Evacuation orders for close to 5,000 people are still in place as firefighters battle a deadly blaze in New Mexico. The wind-fueled flames have destroyed more than 200 homes and killed two people since the wildfire broke out Tuesday.
More than 900 bodies of civilians have been discovered in the Kyiv region following the withdrawal of Russian forces. Most were shot dead. Police say they were likely “simply executed.”

Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida and visiting U.S. lawmakers have reaffirmed their commitment to working together under a longstanding bilateral alliance, amid global tensions spanning the war in Ukraine to threats from neighboring China and N. Korea.

Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy is calling for "the democratic world" to ban Russian oil, saying existing sanctions against Moscow are painful but not enough to stop the Russian military's ongoing assault.

Three Chinese astronauts have returned to Earth after six months aboard their country’s newest orbital station. During the mission, astronaut Wang Yaping carried out the first spacewalk by a Chinese woman.

Employees at Verizon stores north of Seattle have won their union election, making them the first unionized Verizon stores in the country outside of New York. The near-unanimous victory represents the latest in a growing labor movement across the country.

A judge has ruled that a man charged with killing 10 people at a Colorado supermarket last year is still mentally incompetent to stand trial, further delaying court proceedings in the case. But the judge also said that assessment could change soon.

Gerda Weissmann Klein, a Holocaust survivor, author, and recipient of the Presidential Medal of Freedom, died on April 3. She was 97.

Klein was born May 8, 1924, in Bielsko, Poland, and was a teenager when the Nazis invaded the country.

A New Mexico village braces for more hot, dry and windy conditions after a deadly blaze destroyed more than 200 homes. 

Just a decade ago Ruidoso recorded the most destructive wildfire in New Mexico's history when more than 240 homes burned.

BREAKING: The Wisconsin Supreme Court has adopted GOP-drawn maps for the state Legislature, after initially approving maps drawn by Democratic Gov. Tony Evers. The reversal comes after the U.S. Supreme Court said Evers' maps were incorrectly adopted.

“Tears do not let me watch until the end.”

Viktoria Kovalenko bore witness to the death of her husband and daughter when their car was hit by a shell in northern Ukraine. She was only able to watch their funeral through cellphone video, weeks later.

Liz Sheridan, who played doting mom to Jerry Seinfeld on his hit sitcom, died early Friday. She was 93.

Sheridan’s “Seinfeld” role as Helen was her best known, but followed decades of work on stage and screen.

The Biden administration is sharply raising rates for royalties companies must pay for oil and natural gas extracted from federal lands as it moves forward under court order with sales of public fossil fuel reserves in nine states.

Author JD Vance has received Donald Trump’s coveted endorsement in the race for Ohio’s open U.S. Senate seat. The decision ends months of jockeying in a Republican Senate primary where his backing could be pivotal.

Twitter wants to thwart billionaire Elon Musk's takeover bid with a so-called "poison pill" -- a financial device that companies have been using for decades to fend off unwelcome suitors. Here's a look at how it could play out:

Baseball legends, fans and family gathered in New York to celebrate Jackie Robinson Day.

Players across the majors will don Robinson’s No. 42 — and all of them in Dodger blue this year — for the 75th anniversary of his big league debut.

BREAKING: Texas Gov. Greg Abbott has repealed his traffic-clogging immigration order that backed up commercial trucks at the U.S.-Mexico border this week.

This comes after a week of intensifying backlash and fears of deepening economic losses.

Body camera footage of Patrick Lyoya’s fatal encounter with a Michigan police officer goes dark 42 seconds before the officer shoots the Black man in the head.

It’s the latest in a handful of high-profile cases in which body cameras have somehow failed.

President Joe Biden and the first lady earned $610,702 during their first year in the White House and paid $150,439 in federal income taxes.

It's the second year Biden has released his tax returns from the White House.

Muslim headscarves are center stage in France’s presidential campaign amid candidate Marine Le Pen’s push to ban them.

She and her rival, President Emmanuel Macron, were confronted by women who asked why their clothing should be caught up in politics.

Victoria Kovalenko's family car was hit with a Russian shell as they were fleeing Chernihiv on the ninth day after the invasion of Ukraine.

Her 12-year-old daughter Veronika and husband Petro were killed in the attack.

More and more Americans who get help buying groceries through the federal food stamp program are seeing their benefits plunge.

This comes as the nation struggles with the biggest increase in food costs in decades.

Broadway theatergoers will have to keep their masks up through at least May 31.

The announcement comes as the U.S. deals with a COVID-19 surge, with cases rising nationally and in most states after a two-month decline.

“Then it kicked in. Get them out.”

Train driver David Artis and his fellow transit workers were honored by the New York City mayor for their response to Tuesday’s subway shooting in Brooklyn.

Texas Gov. Greg Abbott's decision to impose additional inspections of trucks entering from Mexico is his latest move in an unprecedented foray into border security.

Here are some facts about conditions on the border and Abbott's response:

Relatives of some of the 20 children and six educators killed in the 2012 Newtown, Connecticut, massacre sued Jones for defamation. A judge found Jones liable for damages, and a trial on how much he should pay the families is set for August.

Infowars host and conspiracy theorist Alex Jones will be getting back the $75,000 in fines he paid to a Connecticut court for missing a deposition last month in a lawsuit over his assertions that the Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting was a hoax.

A spokesman for the fishing industry’s main lobby group said that the group’s members are now reviewing their sourcing practices.

But some fear an outright ban on third-party processed seafood could lead to job losses in the U.S. and add to inflation.

Fishing is big business in Russia, one linked to Putin’s projection of power at sea. Exports to the U.S. last year hit $1.2 billion.

But it’s unknown how much of that comes by way of China. Nor does a ban on Russian seafood require importers to find out.

A U.S. ban on seafood imports from Russia was supposed to sap billions of dollars from Vladimir Putin’s war machine.

But shortcomings in import regulations means that Russian-caught fish are likely to enter the U.S. anyway, by way of China.
Dozens of Republican leaders in Ohio are mounting a last-minute effort to urge former President Donald Trump not to endorse JD Vance in the crowded upcoming primary for an open Senate seat.

BREAKING: A senior U.S. defense official says the U.S. believes the Russian guided-missile cruiser that sank in the northern Black Sea was struck by at least one Ukrainian anti-ship missile, as claimed by the Kyiv government.

BREAKING: Iowa Supreme Court rules that Democratic Senate candidate Abby Finkenauer qualifies for the primary ballot, allowing her to continue her campaign for the nomination and the chance to face longtime Republican Sen. Charles Grassley.

Twitter said the move aims to enable its investors to “realize the full value of their investment” in the company by reducing the likelihood that any one person can gain control without paying shareholders a premium or giving the board more time.
BREAKING: Twitter, in a statement, said its board of directors has unanimously adopted a “poison pill” defense in response to Tesla CEO Elon Musk’s proposal to buy the company and take it private.
With the largest populations of Muslims and Jews in western Europe, the issue has major potential repercussions for France and could hit communities elsewhere that buy French meat exports.

France's far-right presidential candidate Marine Le Pen wants to outlaw ritual slaughter if elected, saying animals should be stunned before slaughter.

That’s unacceptable to observant Jews and Muslims who say stunning causes unnecessary animal suffering.

A South Carolina prisoner scheduled to be the first man executed in the state in more than a decade has decided to die by firing squad rather than in the electric chair later this month, according to court documents.

More than 900 civilian bodies were discovered in the Kyiv, Ukraine, area following the withdrawal of Russian forces, the regional police chief said, citing police data indicating that 95% of the casualties had died from sniper fire and gunshot wounds.

Sherman Peebles, a sheriff’s deputy, died of COVID-19 in late September, 2021. Widely known in his community as Uncle Sherman, his funeral service was held in a local skating rink to make room for the estimated 300 mourners. 
 
This is his story.

Most states keep paper records of every ballot cast in elections. Five of the six holdouts are Republican-led. 

Most of them now have plans to start creating paper records, partially in response to false claims about the 2020 presidential election race.

Two years after the pandemic hit the economy, America’s auto market looks something like this: Prices are up. Supply is down. And gasoline costs drastically more. The result? A widening disparity between the richest buyers and everyone else.

The U.S. is trudging into what could be another COVID-19 surge, with cases rising nationally and in most states after a two-month decline.

Experts warn that the coming wave will push up hospitalizations in a growing number of states.
A former University of Michigan violin professor has been sentenced to five years in prison after pleading guilty to transporting a girl across state lines for sex.

New York Gov. Kathy Hochul will have to navigate the sudden arrest and resignation of her running mate and lieutenant governor on bribery charges as she tries to win her party’s nomination in June. But it’s unclear whether it will endanger her primary bid.

A decommissioned World War II-era destroyer docked near downtown Buffalo in New York is taking on water.

Crews were working to keep the USS The Sullivans from sinking at its berth at the Buffalo and Erie County Naval & Military Park, where it had been open for tours.

New York Islanders great Mike Bossy has died after a battle with lung cancer at age 65. Bossy helped the Islanders win the Stanley Cup from 1980-83 and scored 50 or more goals in each of his first nine seasons. Bossy played his entire career with New York.

“I protect the public interest of Ukrainian citizens. And now I see that I can’t protect these dead kids,” says Ukraine’s prosecutor general Iryna Venediktova. “And for me it’s pain.”

Venediktova's purpose? To make Vladimir Putin and his forces pay for what they have done.
NASA’s latest attempt to fuel its huge moon rocket for a countdown test was thwarted by a hazardous hydrogen leak, the latest in a series of vexing equipment trouble.

A bus carrying worshippers traveling to an Easter pilgrimage in mountainous eastern Zimbabwe plunged into a gorge, killing 35 people. Police said the bus was overloaded with 106 passengers and veered off the winding road.

Virus update: 
• Anti-virus shutdowns in China spread as infections rise.
• California delays virus vaccine mandate for schools.
• FDA OKs first breath test for COVID-19 infection.
• South Korea to remove most pandemic restrictions.

More coverage:
A day in the life of Ukraine Prosecutor General Iryna Venediktova, whose every waking moment is devoted to uncovering war crimes against her people -- and seeking justice.

Unbroken by a weekslong Russian blockade and relentless bombardment, the key port of Mariupol is holding out, a symbol of staunch Ukrainian resistance. Mariupol has been a key objective for Moscow to create a land corridor to the annexed Crimean Peninsula.

These seven people are among the nearly 1 million who have died from COVID-19 in the United States. 

These are their stories, as told by the people left behind.

January 2022. 

Larry Mass and Arnie Kantrowitz were among the New Yorkers who clapped for health workers from their window when the pandemic began. Almost two years later, Kantrowitz, 81, catches COVID. He dies on Jan. 21, as the toll nears 1 million.

September 2021. 

Sherman Peebles, a sheriff’s deputy and barber many in his town called Uncle Sherman, drives himself to the hospital in late August. He dies a month into his fight against COVID, as the U.S. toll surpasses 675,000.

August 2021. 

As people get vaccinated, daily COVID deaths decline. But in Missouri, some hospitals are swamped with unvaccinated patients. Among them is Larry Quackenbush, 60. He dies as the U.S. toll tops 614,000.

December 2020. 

Nurse Jennifer McClung, 54, texts her mother from the hospital: “Mama, I feel like I’m never coming home again.” She dies hours before a nurse in New York receives the nation’s first COVID-19 vaccine, as the U.S. toll passes 300,000.

July 2020. 

Luis Alfonso Bay Montgomery, 59, is rushed to the hospital weeks after falling ill. He dies in mid-July, and the U.S. toll surpasses 140,000. 

His wife says she still sees him sometimes on his tractor or hears him talking to their kids.

April 2020.  

Mary Jacq McCulloch, 87, evades the virus when people first start testing positive at her nursing home. But a month into the pandemic, she gets sick. She dies the day after her children gather at her bedside, in person and by phone.

March 2020.   

Neil Lawyer, 84, goes to a Mardi Gras party at the Seattle-area nursing home where he's recovering from an infection. He falls ill days later and dies on March 8, when the U.S. toll is only 30 and before the virus’ threat is fully in focus.

The COVID-19 death toll in the U.S. is nearing 1 million, a number so big it can feel abstract. But wave after wave, it has left empty spaces, taking lives that touched countless others.

While viruses naturally occur in the wild, human disruption of marine habitats has made animals more vulnerable to outbreaks as stress from pollution and excess boat noise weakens immune systems.

Reducing those disturbances can help dolphins.
To trace the dolphin social networks, scientists have built a "Facebook" of fins — distinguishing more than 2,000 dolphins by the distinctive shapes and markings of their dorsal fins.

To understand how diseases circulate in social animals, scientists must scrutinize not only the biology of a virus, but also how vulnerable populations interact, said Jacob Negrey, a researcher who studies animal viruses at Wake Forest School of Medicine.

Scientists are studying how differences in social behavior may spread the disease.

For example, male dolphins often breathe in sync while females sync too but not as regularly. That may help explain why males die in greater numbers during virus outbreaks.

Dolphins often breathe in sync — surfacing and exhaling at the same time — with family and close pals. It’s a way of affirming the relationships that are so important to these social mammals.

But it can also spread diseases like cetacean morbillivirus.

In the 2020 election, Oregon became the first U.S. state to decriminalize possession of drugs, channeling millions of dollars into programs to help people with substance abuse disorders. The results are mixed.

State governments are ramping up efforts to combat the fentanyl crisis. About two-thirds of the more than 100,000 annual fatal U.S. drug overdoses are linked to fentanyl and other synthetic drugs, which can be many times more potent than heroin.

The half-brother of Jordan’s king has relinquished his princely title, a year after a rare palace feud saw him placed under house arrest. Prince Hamzah posted a letter, saying his values are "not in line with the modern methods of our institutions.”

Russia’s war on Ukraine is bringing new problems to a global auto industry that already was struggling to find key parts. The invasion has choked the supply of electrical wiring made in Ukraine, forcing German automakers to temporarily close factories.

U.S. faith communities are welcoming refugees displaced by the war in Ukraine. In Southern California, pastors are at the Mexico border offering food, water and prayer. Around the country, other groups are preparing to provide longer-term support.

While many states have spent their federal rental assistance, some small, rural states have leftover cash. The federal government is reallocating some the remaining funds.

Nearly 180,000 Americans get the disorder every year, according to The National Aphasia Association.

A man allegedly had himself vaccinated against COVID-19 dozens of times in Germany in order to sell forged vaccination cards with real vaccine batch numbers to people not wanting to get vaccinated. The man, 60, is said to have received up to 90 shots.

As the conflict in Ukraine rages, a vast apparatus is being built to gather and preserve evidence of potential violations of international laws of war.

Here’s a look at what war crimes are and what options exist for bringing those responsible to justice.

Attacks on medical facilities and staff are considered particularly heinous under international law, but bombing a hospital is not necessarily a war crime. 

Prosecutors must show that the destruction is intentional or reckless.

Military attacks on civilian populations and their property are generally forbidden under international laws governing armed conflicts going back more than a century. The U.S. government assessed that members of Russia’s military have committed war crimes.

Russian officials have denied hitting civilian targets, deriding the mounting documentation of atrocities as “Fake News” and claiming without evidence that dead and wounded civilians photographed were “crisis actors.”

Ohmatdyt Children’s Hospital in Kyiv, which houses Ukraine’s primary pediatric cancer center, has repeatedly been rocked by explosions since the war began.

“We must support our patients because, in Kyiv and Ukraine, it’s terrible for everybody.”

Among the most thoroughly documented strikes was the bombing of a children’s and maternity hospital in Mariupol. Two @AP journalists, who arrived minutes after the explosion, captured photos and video of stunned survivors leaving the hospital.

The @AP reports include visual evidence such as time- and location-stamped photos and videos, along with witness accounts. 

AP journalists outside Ukraine have confirmed the details of other attacks by interviewing survivors.

This accounting of attacks on medical facilities is part of the War Crimes Watch project, an online database launched by the @AP and @FrontlinePBS to independently track evidence of potential war crimes committed during the Russia-Ukraine war.

An emerging pattern, tracked by the @AP, shows evidence of a consistent and relentless onslaught against the very civilian infrastructure designed to save lives and provide safe haven to Ukraine’s most vulnerable.

The @AP and @FrontlinePBS have documented at least 34 assaults where Russian forces hit Ukrainian medical facilities, striking at ambulances and hospitals that still have patients.

With every attack, the outcry for war crimes prosecutions grows louder.

The patterns echo the “white flight" that upended urban landscapes in the 20th century. Like those who left cities before them, Black residents often move because of worries about crime and a desire for reputable schools and affordable housing.

Chicago’s Roseland neighborhood alone lost roughly 1,600 Black residents in an area of less than 1 square mile. Meanwhile, 13 miles away, suburban Lansing, Illinois has seen a roughly 50% increase in Black population.

While New York, Los Angeles and Philadelphia all lost Black residents from 2010 to 2020, the change was especially notable in Chicago, according to the U.S. census. Chicago gained population but lost 85,000 Black people, the highest number after Detroit.

For decades, Black residents have been leaving some of the largest cities in the U.S. while suburbs saw Black population growth. From 1990 to 2000, 13 of the biggest cities lost Black residents. By 2020, it was 23.

The current pandemic has progressed in different ways around the world, killing at least 6 million people globally.

But in parts of the world where cases and death rates are falling, there’s hope of entering a new phase.

Those epidemics evolved differently:
• Multiple flu pandemics waned over time.
• HIV became a manageable chronic condition in places with access to new treatments, but remains an emergency in others.
• Cases of Zika dropped dramatically with time.
